<h1>Debian/PowerPC</h1>
<p>
<img src="pics/ppc750.jpg" alt="PPC-750 picture" align="right">
 The PowerPC is a RISC (Reduced Instruction-Set Computing) microprocessor
 developed by <a href="http://www.chips.ibm.com/products/powerpc/">IBM</a>
 and <a href="http://mot-sps.com/">Motorola</a>.
 The first such chip was the 601, released in 1992. After that, the 603 and
 604 series were developed, then 750, also known as the G3, after which came
 the G4 series. See the <a href="http://www.motorola.com/SPS/PowerPC/">
 PowerPC home page</a> for more information.
</p>

<h3> Linux and PowerPC </h3>
<p>
 Linux for the PowerPC hasn't existed for very long in mainstream Linux
 kernel, until 2.2.x versions. Vger was the primary development source
 tree for PowerPC Linux. These days, the primary resource for PowerPC
 Linux development is <a href="http://penguinppc.org/">penguinppc</a>.
</p>

<p>
 Latest released and development Linux PowerPC kernel sources are available
 through <a href="http://packages.debian.org/stable/net/rsync.html">rsync</a>
 at <code>penguinppc.org::linux-pmac-stable</code> and
 <code>penguinppc.org::linux-pmac-devel</code>, respectively (see
 the <a href="http://penguinppc.org/dev/">Developer Info</a> for more
 information).
</p>

<h3> Beginning of the Debian Port </h3>
<p>
 The PowerPC port began in 1997 at the <a href="http://www.linux-kongress.de/">
 German Linux Congress</a> in W&uuml;rzburg. 
 <a href="http://www.infodrom.north.de/Infodrom/tervola.html">A
 PowerPC machine</a> (Motorola StarMax 4000, 200 MHz 604e) was donated to
 the Debian project and it is hosted by Martin "Joey" Schulze.
</p>

<p>
 This machine is still in use as an <em>automatic package build daemon</em>,
 it creates Debian packages for all new source files.
</p>

<p>
 Additional information about this computer is available from
 <a href="history">the history page</a>.
</p> 


<h3>Status</h3>
<p>
 Debian/PowerPC was officially released with Debian GNU/Linux 2.2, `potato'.
 Please see the <a href="$(HOME)/releases/potato/powerpc/release-notes/">
 release notes</a> and the <a href="$(HOME)/releases/potato/powerpc/install">
 installation manual</a> for the PowerPC architecture.
</p>

<h2>FTP/HTTP Access</h2>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p>
   Packages are available on any complete Debian mirror. Packages are arranged
   in subdirectories, according to the version, stability, and platform.
   Thus binary packages are available from the 
   <a href="ftp://ftp.debian.org/debian/dists/potato/main/binary-powerpc/">
   /debian/dists/potato/main/binary-powerpc/</a>
   directory on any Debian mirror. (The link is to the main Debian site; you
   should probably use a nearby 
   <a href="$(HOME)/misc/README.mirrors">mirror site</a>.)
   <br>
   <br>
   Source packages are available from the same sites, in the directory 
   <a href="ftp://ftp.debian.org/debian/dists/potato/main/source/">
   /debian/dists/potato/main/source/</a>.
  </p>
 </li>
 <li>
  <p>
   Using the <a href="http://packages.debian.org/">WWW interface to
   packages</a> will allow you to view packages by distribution and search
   for package names and strings in package descriptions.
  </p>
 </li>
</ul>

